# Agent contract — {{ project_name }}

This repository runs the infrastructure of **{{ community_name }}**:
a single-node k3s cluster on {{ server_ipv4 }} ({{ target_arch }}), GitOps
via Flux, central identity via ZITADEL at `id.{{ domain }}`. It is generated
from [citadel-stack-template](https://github.com/levino/citadel-stack-template)
and is designed so that **you, the agent, can build and operate it from
zero** — the human is product owner, not operator.

Read this file first. For any non-trivial operation there is a runbook:

- Build everything from scratch: `runbooks/bootstrap-from-zero.md`
- Known footguns (read BEFORE debugging): `runbooks/incidents/`
- ZITADEL bootstrap secrets: `zitadel/SECRETS.md`
- Identity as code: `tofu/zitadel/README.md`
- Adding apps: `apps/README.md` and `patterns/`

## Invariants (hard rules — never break, never "temporarily" bypass)

1. **GitOps is the single source of truth.** No manual `kubectl apply`
   outside the documented bootstrap steps. To change the cluster, change
   this repo. If you find drift, fix the repo, not the cluster.
2. **Never `cluster-admin` for CI/OIDC identities.** CI identities get the
   `preview-deployer` ClusterRole via namespace-scoped RoleBinding only
   (`scripts/new-app.sh` does this correctly).
3. **App-bound secrets enter this repo only as SealedSecrets** (OIDC client
   credentials, cookie secrets — they belong to an app and rotate with it).
   Seal offline against `sealed-secrets-public-key.pem`.
   **Operational access tokens (PATs) NEVER enter the repo — not even
   sealed.** A PAT is a broad, long-lived credential; sealing it leaves a
   permanent encrypted blob in git history and couples a personal token to
   the repo. Create such credentials directly in the cluster
   (`kubectl create secret …`) and record the command in a runbook so the
   cluster can be rebuilt. This is the one sanctioned exception to invariant
   1. Never commit plaintext secrets, never echo secrets into logs.
4. **Images must run on {{ target_arch }} — built on NATIVE runners, never
   QEMU.** Build each architecture on its own native GitHub runner
   (`ubuntu-24.04-arm` for arm64, `ubuntu-latest` for amd64) and merge them
   into one manifest list with `docker buildx imagetools create`. Do NOT use
   QEMU/cross-emulation (`docker/setup-qemu-action`, or a single-job
   `platforms: linux/amd64,linux/arm64` build) — it is slow and has shipped
   broken images here. A pull that works on your machine proves nothing.
5. **Identity is declarative.** Orgs, projects, roles, OIDC clients live in
   `tofu/zitadel/` — not in the ZITADEL UI. UI is for humans doing
   self-service member management, nothing else.
6. **ZITADEL is an IdP, not a CRM.** Domain data (fees, join dates,
   membership numbers) belongs in app databases, keyed by the token `sub`.
7. **Single node, single replica is a feature** (cheap infra). Do not add
   HA machinery.

## Layout

| Path | What | Propagation |
|---|---|---|
| `flux/` | GitOps entry point (GitRepository + Kustomizations) | applied once at bootstrap, then self-managed |
| `cluster/` | substrate: traefik, cert-manager, sealed-secrets, rbac | Flux |
| `zitadel/` | ZITADEL + Postgres + sealed bootstrap secrets | Flux (separate Kustomization — fails until secrets are sealed) |
| `apps/` | one entry per app — stamped by `scripts/new-app.sh` | Flux |
| `tofu/zitadel/` | identity as code (org/projects/roles/clients) | `tofu apply` (local) |
| `patterns/` | copyable recipes: native OIDC, ForwardAuth, app deploy CI | read, copy, adapt |
| `runbooks/` | bootstrap + incidents | read |

## Verify commands (use these before declaring anything healthy)

```bash
flux get kustomizations          # all Ready=True
flux get helmreleases -A         # traefik, zitadel-postgresql, zitadel Ready
kubectl get pods -A | grep -v Running | grep -v Completed   # should be empty
kubectl get certificates -A      # all Ready=True
curl -fsS https://id.{{ domain }}/.well-known/openid-configuration | head -3
kubectl describe node | grep -A5 Conditions   # no DiskPressure (see incidents/)
```

## Operating rules of thumb

- A change is deployed when Flux has reconciled it — verify with
  `flux get kustomizations`, not by assuming.
- If a HelmRelease hangs >30s in install: pull the pod logs of its
  init/setup hooks IMMEDIATELY (see `runbooks/incidents/zitadel-bootstrap.md`,
  lesson learned).
- After every real incident: write `runbooks/incidents/<date>-<slug>.md`
  (what happened, root cause, fix, prevention). If the lesson generalizes,
  open a PR against the template repo — that is the feedback loop.
- The issuer is named `acme` in every environment. Do not rename it, do not
  hardcode ACME URLs anywhere outside `cluster/cert-manager/issuer.yaml`.
